      core: "Context switching saves/restores registers, program counter, and stack pointer, then resumes a different execution path. The new thread may cause L1/L2 cache misses.",
      deep: "The cost is not only kernel bookkeeping. After switching, the new thread often touches different memory, causing cold cache lines and branch predictor misses. A tiny cache get can become slower if the system is drowning in thread switches.",
      concepts: [["Runnable vs running", "Many threads can be ready; only core-count threads run at once."], ["Direct cost", "Scheduler saves/restores execution state."], ["Indirect cost", "Cache locality is lost."], ["Latency", "Switching increases tail latency under load."]],
      examples: [["Web server", "Too many request threads increase switching and queueing."], ["GC pause", "Application threads stop and resume, creating spikes."], ["Redis-Lite", "Do not create a new thread for every get or put."]],
