      core: "Each thread has its own stack. The Java heap is shared by all threads in the JVM process.",
      deep: "The JVM may keep locals in registers, stack slots, or optimize them away. The interview model remains: local frame is private; heap object is shared if reachable by many threads.",
      concepts: [["Thread stack", "Per-thread call frames and locals."], ["Heap", "Shared dynamic allocation area."], ["Reference", "Local pointer to heap object."], ["Escape analysis", "JVM can optimize non-escaping allocations." ]],
      examples: [["Local counter", "int count inside method is thread-local."], ["Shared map", "ConcurrentHashMap field is shared heap."], ["LRU node", "Local reference may point to shared node." ]],
      flow: ["Method called", "Stack frame created", "Objects allocated if needed", "Frame popped on return", "Reachable heap object remains"],
      tradeoffs: [["Stack", "Fast and thread-confined."], ["Heap", "Flexible sharing, needs GC/synchronization."], ["Immutable object", "Safe sharing after construction." ]],
      failures: ["Believing local reference means local object.", "Sharing mutable objects without synchronization.", "Ignoring stack overflow from recursion."],
      useWhen: ["Explaining visibility and shared state."],
      avoidWhen: ["Do not expose internal heap objects directly from cache API."],
      code: "class CacheService {\n    private final ConcurrentHashMap<String, Entry> store = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();\n    Entry get(String key) {\n        Entry localRef = store.get(key);\n        return localRef;\n    }\n}",
      questions: [["EASY", "Do threads share stacks?", "No. Each thread has its own stack."], ["MEDIUM", "Can a local variable lead to shared mutation?", "Yes, if it references a shared heap object."], ["HARD", "Why important for Redis-Lite?", "Map, entries, and LRU nodes live on shared heap and need safe access." ]],
      revision: "Stack is per-thread; heap is shared; references connect them."
